Program 2: Create Storage Space Using Amazon S3 (GUI Only)
Aim

To create an Amazon S3 bucket, upload files, organize data, configure permissions, and access files using CloudFront through the AWS Management Console.

Step 1: Login to AWS
Open your browser.
Visit https://aws.amazon.com/
Click Sign In to Console.
Enter your AWS account credentials.
After login, the AWS Management Console opens.

Explanation:
The AWS Management Console is a graphical interface used to create and manage AWS services without typing commands.

Step 2: Open Amazon S3
In the search bar, type S3.
Click Amazon S3.

Explanation:
Amazon S3 (Simple Storage Service) is an object storage service where data is stored inside Buckets.

Step 3: Create an S3 Bucket
Click Create bucket.
Select
Bucket type: General Purpose
Enter a bucket name.

Example:

suhas-cloud-storage-2026

The bucket name

must be unique worldwide
use only lowercase letters
numbers and hyphens are allowed
no spaces
Select Region

Example

Asia Pacific (Mumbai)
ap-south-1
Leave Object Ownership
ACLs Disabled (Recommended)
Leave Block Public Access

Keep all four check boxes selected.

Leave Bucket Versioning
Disabled
Leave Default Encryption
Server-side encryption with Amazon S3 managed keys (SSE-S3)
Click

Create Bucket

Explanation:

A bucket is like a folder in cloud storage where files are stored.

Step 4: Verify Bucket Creation

The bucket will appear in the S3 bucket list.

Click the bucket name.

Initially the bucket is empty.

Step 5: Upload Files

Inside the bucket

Click

Upload

Then

Add Files

or

Add Folder

Select

Example

index.html

style.css

image.jpg

Click

Upload

Wait until the upload is completed.

Click Close.

Explanation

Objects are the files stored inside the S3 bucket.

Step 6: View Uploaded Files

Open the bucket.

You should see

index.html

style.css

image.jpg

Click any file.

You can see

Object name
Size
Last modified
Storage class
Step 7: Create Folder (Optional)

Inside bucket

Click

Create Folder

Example

Images

Open the folder.

Upload image files.

Explanation

Folders help organize data inside the bucket.

Step 8: Copy Objects Between Buckets (GUI)

If required

Create another bucket.

Open first bucket.

Select a file.

Click

Actions

↓

Copy

Open second bucket.

Click

Paste

The file is copied.

Step 9: Delete Objects

Select a file.

Click

Delete

Type

permanently delete

Click

Delete Objects

Step 10: Enable Static Website Hosting

Open your bucket.

Select

Properties

Scroll to

Static Website Hosting

Click

Edit

Choose

Enable

Hosting type

Host a Static Website

Index document

index.html

Error document

error.html

(Optional)

Click

Save Changes

Explanation

This makes the bucket capable of hosting a website.

Step 11: Create CloudFront Distribution

Search

CloudFront

Open it.

Click

Create Distribution

Origin Domain

Click inside the Origin field.

Select your S3 bucket.

Example

suhas-cloud-storage-2026
Origin Access

Choose

Origin Access Control Settings (Recommended)
Create OAC

Click

Create New OAC

Leave default values.

Click

Create

The new Origin Access Control will be selected.

Web Application Firewall (WAF)

Choose

Do Not Enable Security Protection

Leave all remaining settings as default.

Click

Create Distribution

Explanation

CloudFront securely delivers S3 content using Amazon's global network, making websites faster and more secure.

Step 12: Wait for Distribution Deployment

Status will show

Deploying

Wait around

10–15 minutes

until it changes to

Deployed
Step 13: Copy CloudFront Domain Name

Open the CloudFront distribution.

Copy

Distribution Domain Name

Example

d2abcxyz123.cloudfront.net
Step 14: Update Bucket Policy

Go back to

Amazon S3

↓

Open Bucket

↓

Permissions

↓

Bucket Policy

↓

Edit

Replace the policy with the following template:

{
  "Version":"2012-10-17",
  "Statement":[
    {
      "Sid":"AllowCloudFrontAccessOnly",
      "Effect":"Allow",
      "Principal":{
        "Service":"cloudfront.amazonaws.com"
      },
      "Action":"s3:GetObject",
      "Resource":"arn:aws:s3:::YOUR_BUCKET_NAME/*",
      "Condition":{
        "StringEquals":{
          "AWS:SourceArn":"arn:aws:cloudfront::YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:distribution/YOUR_DISTRIBUTION_ID"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}

Replace

YOUR_BUCKET_NAME

YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID

YOUR_DISTRIBUTION_ID

with your actual values.

Click

Save Changes

Explanation of Bucket Policy

Version

Policy language version.

Effect

Allows access.

Principal

CloudFront service.

Action

Allows reading objects.

Resource

Specifies all files inside your bucket.

Condition

Only your CloudFront distribution can access the bucket.

Step 15: Test Website

Open browser.

Paste

https://CloudFront_Domain_Name/index.html

Example

https://d2abcxyz123.cloudfront.net/index.html

Your webpage should open.
